<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">Diagnosis</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">This species is characterised by unarmed leaves and narrowly cylindrical hairy burrs 2-3 cm long with numerous, closely spaced hooked prickles.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">Distribution</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" type="native distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">Native distribution</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">
This species is native to North America and South America (
<bibRefCitation author="Loeve, Doris" journalOrPublisher="Canadian Journal of Botany" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" pagination="173 - 208" refId="B7199524" refString="Loeve, Doris, Dansereau, Pierre, 1959. Biosystematic studies on Xanthium: Taxonomic appraisal and ecological status. Canadian Journal of Botany 37 (2): 173 - 208" title="Biosystematic studies on Xanthium: Taxonomic appraisal and ecological status" volume="37" year="1959">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Löve">Loeve</normalizedToken>
and Dansereau 1959
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" type="secondary distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">Secondary distribution</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">Neophyte in Europe, Mediterranean, South Africa, Western, Boreal, Central and Tropical Asia, Australia.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">
In arid regions of Asia, the species was known from several localities in Iran already 40 years ago (
<bibRefCitation author="Dittrich, M." journalOrPublisher="Flora Iranica" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" refId="B7378342" refString="Dittrich, M., 1989. . Flora Iranica 164" volume="164" year="1989">Dittrich 1989</bibRefCitation>
). In China, it was recorded for the first time in Beijing in 1991 (as 
<taxonomicName genus="X." lsidName="X. italicum" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" rank="species" species="italicum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">X. italicum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: 
<bibRefCitation author="Xu, Haigen" journalOrPublisher="NeoBiota" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" pagination="1 - 26" refId="B7422346" refString="Xu, Haigen, Qiang, Sheng, Genovesi, Piero, Ding, Hui, Wu, Jun, Meng, Ling, Han, Zhengmin, Miao, Jinlai, Hu, Baishi, Guo, Jiangying, Sun, Hongying, Huang, Cheng, Lei, Juncheng, Le, Zhifang, Zhang, Xiaoping, He, Shunping, Wu, Yu, Zheng, Zhou, Chen, Lian, Jarosik, Vojtech, Pysek, Petr, 2012. An inventory of invasive alien species in China. NeoBiota 15: 1 - 26" title="An inventory of invasive alien species in China" volume="15" year="2012">Xu et al. 2012</bibRefCitation>
). In Russian Asia, it is known from many localities in southern Siberia (
<bibRefCitation author="Khanminchun, V. M." journalOrPublisher="Flora of Siberia" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" refId="B7422414" refString="Khanminchun, V. M., 1998. . Flora of Siberia 13" volume="13" year="1998">Khanminchun 1998</bibRefCitation>
) and the southern Far East (
<bibRefCitation author="Kozhevnikov, A. E." journalOrPublisher="Komarovskie Chteniya" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" pagination="5 - 36" refId="B7422436" refString="Kozhevnikov, A. E., Kozhevnikova, Z. V., 2011. Alien species plant complex as a component of the Russian Far East natural flora: diversity and regional changes of taxonomical structure. Komarovskie Chteniya 58: 5 - 36" title="Alien species plant complex as a component of the Russian Far East natural flora: diversity and regional changes of taxonomical structure" volume="58" year="2011">Kozhevnikov and Kozhevnikova 2011</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" type="distribution in central asia">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">Distribution in Central Asia</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Tajikistan, Uzbekistan.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">
In Kazakhstan (as 
<taxonomicName genus="X." lsidName="X. albinum" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" rank="species" species="albinum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">X. albinum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: 
<bibRefCitation author="Ebel, A. L." journalOrPublisher="Botanicheskii Zhurnal" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" pagination="131 - 135" refId="B7199542" refString="Ebel, A. L., Ebel, T. V., 2003. New records of plants from Eastern Kazakhstan. Botanicheskii Zhurnal 88 (10): 131 - 135" title="New records of plants from Eastern Kazakhstan" volume="88" year="2003">Ebel and Ebel 2003</bibRefCitation>
), it was first found as ruderal in Tekeli Town (Almaty Region; Dzungarian Alatau), 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Öskemen">Oeskemen</normalizedToken>
[Ust-Kamenogorsk] Town and north-west of Semei Town (East Kazakhstan Region; Altay Mts.); the first record (specimen dated 1955) was registered near Semei Town. Its latest records from the lowland parts of the country (
<normalizedToken originalValue="Qarağandy">Qaragandy</normalizedToken>
Region, 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Aqtoğai">Aqtogai</normalizedToken>
District, riversides and ruderal places; Pavlodar Region, 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Ekіbastūz">Ekіbastūz</normalizedToken>
Town, ruderal places; 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Túrkistan">Turkistan</normalizedToken>
, Qyzylorda and East Kazakhstan Regions) indicate a greater distribution (as 
<taxonomicName genus="X." lsidName="X. albinum" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" rank="species" species="albinum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">X. albinum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: 
<bibRefCitation author="Nobis, Marcin" journalOrPublisher="Acta Botanica Gallica" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" pagination="103 - 115" refId="B7275256" refString="Nobis, Marcin, Nowak, Arkadiusz, Ebel, Aleksandr L., Nobis, Agnieszka, Nowak, Sylwia, Gudkova, Polina D., Verkhozina, Alla V., Erst, Andrey S., Lazarski, Grzegorz, Olonova, Marina V., Piwowarczyk, Renata, Bobrov, Alexander A., Khrustaleva, Irina A., Plasek, Vitezslav, Silantyeva, Marina M., Zalewska-Galosz, Joanna, 2015. Contribution to the flora of Asian and European countries: new national and regional vascular plant records, 3. Acta Botanica Gallica 162 (2): 103 - 115" title="Contribution to the flora of Asian and European countries: new national and regional vascular plant records, 3" volume="162" year="2015">Nobis et al. 2015</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Ebel, A. L." journalOrPublisher="Botanicheskie Issledovaniya Sibiri i Kazakhstana" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" pagination="35 - 42" refId="B7343486" refString="Ebel, A. L., Kupriyanov, A. N., Laschinsky, N. N., Khrustaleva, I. A., 2016. Additions to the flora of the Boralday branch of the Syrdarya-Turkestan Nature Park. Botanicheskie Issledovaniya Sibiri i Kazakhstana 22: 35 - 42" title="Additions to the flora of the Boralday branch of the Syrdarya-Turkestan Nature Park" volume="22" year="2016">Ebel et al. 2016</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Pagad, Shyama" journalOrPublisher="Scientific Data" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" refId="B7336322" refString="Plantarium Plants and lichens of Russia and neighboring countries: open online galleries and plant identification guide https://www.plantarium.ru/lang/en.html 2021-07-12T00:00:00+03:00" year="2018">Plantarium 2021</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">
In Tajikistan (as 
<taxonomicName genus="X." lsidName="X. californicum" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" rank="species" species="californicum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">X. californicum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: 
<bibRefCitation author="Kinzikaeva, G. K." journalOrPublisher="Flora of the Tajik SSR" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" refId="B7411429" refString="Kinzikaeva, G. K., 1988. . Flora of the Tajik SSR 9" volume="9" year="1988">Kinzikaeva 1988</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Nabiev, M. M." journalOrPublisher="Manual of vascular plants of Central Asia" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" refId="B7199560" refString="Nabiev, M. M., 1993. . Manual of vascular plants of Central Asia 10" volume="10" year="1993">Nabiev 1993</bibRefCitation>
), the species was recorded as a ruderal from two places, at Zafarobod Town and Dushanbe City.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">
In Uzbekistan (as 
<taxonomicName genus="X." lsidName="X. californicum" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" rank="species" species="californicum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">X. californicum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: 
<bibRefCitation author="Nabiev, M. M." journalOrPublisher="Manual of vascular plants of Central Asia" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" refId="B7199560" refString="Nabiev, M. M., 1993. . Manual of vascular plants of Central Asia 10" volume="10" year="1993">Nabiev 1993</bibRefCitation>
; as 
<taxonomicName genus="X." lsidName="X. albinum" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" rank="species" species="albinum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">X. albinum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: 
<bibRefCitation author="Esanov, H." journalOrPublisher="Turczaninowia" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" pagination="77 - 81" refId="B7199551" refString="Esanov, H., 2016. New plant species in the flora of Bukhara oasis. Turczaninowia 19 (2): 77 - 81" title="New plant species in the flora of Bukhara oasis" volume="19" year="2016">Esanov 2016</bibRefCitation>
), the species was known as a weed in Tashkent (first record dated 1986) and as widely naturalised on cotton fields, fallow fields and roadsides of the Buxaro Agricultural Oasis (first recorded in 2007 but apparently established long before). Further records (
<bibRefCitation author="Pagad, Shyama" journalOrPublisher="Scientific Data" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" refId="B7336322" refString="Plantarium Plants and lichens of Russia and neighboring countries: open online galleries and plant identification guide https://www.plantarium.ru/lang/en.html 2021-07-12T00:00:00+03:00" year="2018">Plantarium 2021</bibRefCitation>
) suggest its broad distribution in the Fergana Depression. The high impact of the species on cotton fields in Uzbekistan (
<bibRefCitation author="Esanov, H." journalOrPublisher="Turczaninowia" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" pagination="77 - 81" refId="B7199551" refString="Esanov, H., 2016. New plant species in the flora of Bukhara oasis. Turczaninowia 19 (2): 77 - 81" title="New plant species in the flora of Bukhara oasis" volume="19" year="2016">Esanov 2016</bibRefCitation>
) agrees with the reports from the USA (
<bibRefCitation author="Weaver, S. E." journalOrPublisher="Canadian Journal of Plant Science" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" pagination="211 - 225" refId="B7351393" refString="Weaver, S. E., Lechowicz, M. J., 1983. The biology of Canadian weeds: 56. Xanthium strumarium L. Canadian Journal of Plant Science 63 (1): 211 - 225" title="The biology of Canadian weeds: 56. Xanthium strumarium L." volume="63" year="1983">Weaver and Lechowicz 1983</bibRefCitation>
), but a diversity of Central Asian reports from ruderal habitats suggests its multiple introductions not limited to the cotton cultivation.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">Formally reported for the first time from Kyrgyzstan here.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">The first record of the species from Central Asia (dated 1955) seems to be linked with the infamous Virgin Lands campaign, which started in 1954 as the extensive cultivation of previously uncultivated lands in northern Kazakhstan. To increase the yield of wheat crops, quality seed of productive varieties of American origin seem to have been partly used.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">
The large-scale invasion of 
<taxonomicName genus="X." lsidName="X. orientale" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" rank="species" species="orientale">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">X. orientale</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, however, occurred later, in the 1960s, when the extensive import of North American (largely Canadian) grain (wheat and maize) started to compensate for the shortage of domestic grain and fodder (
<bibRefCitation author="Chistyakov, Y. F." journalOrPublisher="Dokument. Arkhiv. Istoriya. Sovremennost" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" pagination="163 - 169" refId="B7379741" refString="Chistyakov, Y. F., 2009. Grain import in the USSR in 1970s-1980s. Dokument. Arkhiv. Istoriya. Sovremennost 10: 163 - 169" title="Grain import in the USSR in 1970 s- 1980 s" volume="10" year="2009">Chistyakov 2009</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Everitt, J. H." journalOrPublisher="Texas Tech University Press, Lubbock" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" refId="B7379715" refString="FAO FAOSTAT. Statistical database of the Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations http://www.fao.org/faostat/en/home 2021-08-06T00:00:00+03:00" year="2007">FAO 2021</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" type="distribution in kyrgyzstan">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">Distribution in Kyrgyzstan</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">
Western Tian-Shan, Northern Tian-Shan, Alay-Turkestan (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="F7430517" captionText="Figure 8. Distribution of Xanthium orientale in Kyrgyzstan according to herbarium specimens and our observations." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.9.e75590.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/591063" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">8</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">
In Kyrgyzstan, this species was rather neglected. 
<bibRefCitation author="Deza, M. I." journalOrPublisher="Kyrgyzstan, Frunze" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" refId="B7206684" refString="Deza, M. I., 1983. Weedy plants of Kirghizia. Kyrgyzstan, Frunze" title="Weedy plants of Kirghizia" year="1983">Deza (1983)</bibRefCitation>
clearly distinguished it from the typical 
<taxonomicName genus="X." lsidName="X. strumarium" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" rank="species" species="strumarium">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">X. strumarium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
L. and stated that it was found most commonly in (but not restricted to) the 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Chü">Chue</normalizedToken>
Depression, where it occurred along roadsides and irrigation ditches, in populated places, on fallow fields and field margins, in gardens and on cultivated fields. 
<bibRefCitation author="Deza, M. I." journalOrPublisher="Kyrgyzstan, Frunze" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" refId="B7206684" refString="Deza, M. I., 1983. Weedy plants of Kirghizia. Kyrgyzstan, Frunze" title="Weedy plants of Kirghizia" year="1983">Deza (1983)</bibRefCitation>
misapplied the name 
<taxonomicName genus="X." lsidName="X. sibiricum" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" rank="species" species="sibiricum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">X. sibiricum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Patr. ex Widder, which she seemingly borrowed from 
<bibRefCitation author="Smolianinova, L. A." journalOrPublisher="Flora of the USSR" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" refId="B7206721" refString="Smolianinova, L. A., 1959. . Flora of the USSR 25" volume="25" year="1959">Smolianinova (1959)</bibRefCitation>
through 
<bibRefCitation author="Gorbunova, N. V." journalOrPublisher="Flora of Kirghizia" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" refId="B7206708" refString="Gorbunova, N. V., 1965. . Flora of Kirghizia 11" volume="11" year="1965">Gorbunova (1965)</bibRefCitation>
, to this species in spite of their contrasting morphology, thus assuming its native distribution area stretching from Siberia to Central Asia. Due to this incorrect nomenclature, the species was omitted from the recent checklist of the flora of Kyrgyzstan (
<bibRefCitation author="Lazkov, G. A." journalOrPublisher="Finnish Museum of Natural History, Helsinki" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" refId="B7206742" refString="Lazkov, G. A., Sultanova, B. A., 2011. Checklist of vascular plants of Kyrgyzstan. Finnish Museum of Natural History, Helsinki" title="Checklist of vascular plants of Kyrgyzstan" year="2011">Lazkov and Sultanova 2011</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Lazkov, G. A." journalOrPublisher="United Nations Development Programme, Bishkek" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" refId="B7206734" refString="Lazkov, G. A., Sultanova, B. A., 2014. Inventory of the flora of Kyrgyzstan: Vascular plants. United Nations Development Programme, Bishkek" title="Inventory of the flora of Kyrgyzstan: Vascular plants" year="2014">Lazkov and Sultanova 2014</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">
According to herbarium collections, 
<taxonomicName genus="X." lsidName="X. orientale" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" rank="species" species="orientale">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">X. orientale</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurs in a number of localities in or around the 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Chü">Chue</normalizedToken>
, 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Ysyk-Köl">Ysyk-Koel</normalizedToken>
and Fergana Depressions, climbing into the mountains as high as 2200 m and as far as 30 km from the depressions with their high levels of agricultural activity and human population density. Our field observations confirm its currently extensive dispersal (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="F7410935" captionText="Figure 9. Xanthium orientale along the Kyzyl-Suu River, Kyrgyzstan (photo by G. Lazkov, 19 August 2021)." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.9.e75590.figure9" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/580241" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">9</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" type="ecology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">Ecology</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">Gravelly riversides in the native distribution area; disturbed grounds, gravelly roadsides, sandy and gravelly riversides, fallow fields in the secondary distribution area.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" type="biology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">Biology</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">Annual.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">Notes</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">
The modern taxonomic concept in 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Xanthium" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Xanthium" order="Asterales" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">Xanthium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the correct name for this species were established by 
<bibRefCitation author="Greuter, Werner" journalOrPublisher="Willdenowia" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" pagination="245 - 250" refId="B7211916" refString="Greuter, Werner, 2003. The Euro+Med treatment of Senecioneae and the minor Compositae tribes - generic concepts and required new names, with an addendum to Cardueae. Willdenowia 33 (2): 245 - 250" title="The Euro + Med treatment of Senecioneae and the minor Compositae tribes - generic concepts and required new names, with an addendum to Cardueae" volume="33" year="2003">Greuter (2003)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Tomasello, Salvatore" journalOrPublisher="Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" pagination="135 - 145" refId="B7199533" refString="Tomasello, Salvatore, 2018. How many names for a beloved genus? - Coalescent-based species delimitation in Xanthium L. (Ambrosiinae, Asteraceae). Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution 127: 135 - 145" title="How many names for a beloved genus? - Coalescent-based species delimitation in Xanthium L. (Ambrosiinae, Asteraceae)" volume="127" year="2018">Tomasello (2018)</bibRefCitation>
. Our understanding of the diagnostic characters is based on our revision of historical collections and field observations and agrees with the treatment of 
<bibRefCitation author="Nabiev, M. M." journalOrPublisher="Manual of vascular plants of Central Asia" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" refId="B7199560" refString="Nabiev, M. M., 1993. . Manual of vascular plants of Central Asia 10" volume="10" year="1993">Nabiev (1993)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">
The burrs in Central Asian plants are narrowly cylindrical, thus corresponding to 
<taxonomicName genus="X." lsidName="X. orientale subsp. californicum" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" rank="subSpecies" species="orientale" subSpecies="californicum">X. orientale subsp. californicum</taxonomicName>
(Greene) Greuter (incl. 
<taxonomicName genus="X." lsidName="X. chinense" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" rank="species" species="chinense">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">X. chinense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Mill.), as originally identified by 
<bibRefCitation author="Kinzikaeva, G. K." journalOrPublisher="Flora of the Tajik SSR" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" refId="B7411429" refString="Kinzikaeva, G. K., 1988. . Flora of the Tajik SSR 9" volume="9" year="1988">Kinzikaeva (1988)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" type="introduction to kyrgyzstan">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">Introduction to Kyrgyzstan</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" type="period of introduction">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">Period of introduction</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">Neophyte.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">The first collection from Kyrgyzstan (Suzak Town) is dated 1968. We assume that the species had arrived after the Second World War, in the 1960s, as a contaminant of wheat grain of North American origin.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" type="pathways of introduction">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">Pathways of introduction</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">Transport - Contaminant: Seed contaminant.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">
Most likely, the species had arrived as a contaminant of wheat imported from Canada, in agreement with observations in Europe (e.g. 
<bibRefCitation author="Suominen, J." journalOrPublisher="Acta Botanica Fennica" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" pagination="1 - 108" refId="B7434725" refString="Suominen, J., 1979. The grain immigrant flora of Finland. Acta Botanica Fennica 111: 1 - 108" title="The grain immigrant flora of Finland" volume="111" year="1979">Suominen 1979</bibRefCitation>
). In Australia, contamination of cotton seed and animal fur were reported as other main pathways of introduction (
<bibRefCitation author="McMillan, C." journalOrPublisher="Australian Journal of Botany" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" pagination="173 - 192" refId="B7351371" refString="McMillan, C., 1975. The Xanthium strumarium complexes in Australia. Australian Journal of Botany 23: 173 - 192" title="The Xanthium strumarium complexes in Australia" volume="23" year="1975">McMillan 1975</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">Further dispersal occurred with domestic animals, water and transport.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" type="invasion status">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">Invasion status</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">Fully naturalised, highly invasive.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">
Judging from the tendencies in its distribution and expansion, 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Xanthium" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Xanthium orientale" order="Asterales" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="orientale">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">Xanthium orientale</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
seems to be more adapted to the hot arid climate and may have a better prospect of naturalisation than its predecessor, 
<taxonomicName genus="X." lsidName="X. strumarium" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" rank="species" species="strumarium">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">X. strumarium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" type="evidence of impact">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">Evidence of impact</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">Agriculture - major impact (abundant weed of fields, gardens and pastures, contamination of wool). Native ecosystems - major impact (local occurrence along mountain streams and roadsides in mountainous areas, forming extensive monodominant stands). Urban areas - major impact (ruderal occurrence, locally abundant).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="75590" type="trend">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">Trend</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="75590">Rapidly increasing (observed).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
